The paper focuses on pruning convolutional filters in neural networks, which is a common technique in computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the qualitative interpretation of individual filter functionality, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper analyzes the impact of filter pruning on the neural network's functionality, which is related to the field of neural engineering (cs.NE). Finally, the paper discusses the potential impact of filter pruning on natural language processing tasks, which falls under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL).
